---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { site } from "@/data/site";

const transitTrekHref = "https://transittrek.org";
const faqHref = "https://transittrek.org/about";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Transit Treks - Arjun Pherwani"
  description="Transit Treks are public-transit strategy games across Puget Sound. Arjun Pherwani co-created the series and helps organize team logistics and game operations."
  type="article"
  publishedTime={`${site.lastUpdated}T12:00:00.000Z`}
  tags={["public transit", "game design", "logistics", "operations"]}
>
  <article>
    <header class="prose-wrap page-header">
      <p class="mono">Project / community game</p>
      <h1 class="article-title">Transit Treks</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        A recurring public-transit game series across Puget Sound: part scavenger hunt,
        part game of skill and strategy, and part dumb luck.
      </p>
      <div class="project-meta">
        <span>public transit</span>
        <span>game design</span>
        <span>team logistics</span>
        <span>Puget Sound</span>
        <span>co-created</span>
      </div>
      <div class="endlinks">
        <a class="inline-link" href={transitTrekHref} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Transit Trek site</a>
        <a class="inline-link" href={faqHref} target="_blank" rel="noopener">FAQ</a>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="prose-wrap trek-board" aria-label="Simplified Transit Trek route model">
      <div class="trek-line">
        <div class="trek-stop">
          <span>01</span>
          <strong>Start</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="trek-stop">
          <span>02</span>
          <strong>Route</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="trek-stop">
          <span>03</span>
          <strong>Challenge</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="trek-stop">
          <span>04</span>
          <strong>Transfer</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="trek-stop">
          <span>05</span>
          <strong>Finish</strong>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="caption">
        Simplified shape, not an actual route sheet. The game is less about puzzle solving than
        choosing transit moves under shared constraints.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="prose-wrap prose log">
      <h2 class="sub">My Role</h2>
      <p>
        I did not write the code for Transit Treks, but this is still a project I work on from time
        to time. I helped create the event and help organize the human side of it: teams, signups,
        rules, logistics, and day-of coordination.
      </p>

      <h2 class="sub">Game Shape</h2>
      <p>
        Transit Treks are team-based games played on foot and by public transit. The premise changes
        from game to game, but the constant is that teams have a few hours to complete challenges
        while making good route decisions across Seattle and the surrounding transit network.
      </p>
      <p>
        The FAQ describes the game as deliberately not a puzzle hunt. The travel is the challenge:
        teams are navigating constraints, boundaries, transfers, timing, and incomplete information
        while keeping the whole thing light enough to remain fun.
      </p>

      <h2 class="sub">How I Help</h2>
      <ol class="legs">
        <li>
          <span class="leg-tag">Co-creation</span>
          <strong>Helping turn the idea into a repeatable format.</strong>
          Transit Trek started after Jeffrey and I played a transit-based Trek and wanted a version
          with more dynamic, task-oriented game mechanics.
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="leg-tag">Logistics</span>
          <strong>Keeping the team side organized.</strong>
          My lane is team logistics: signups, team formation, participant flow, and the practical
          coordination that keeps a game with dozens of people moving.
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="leg-tag">Operations</span>
          <strong>Helping with the day-of details.</strong>
          The game needs boundaries, permitted travel modes, accessibility choices, late signups,
          and day-of rulings that are clear enough for people to keep playing.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2 class="sub">What I Like About It</h2>
      <ol class="legs">
        <li>
          <span class="leg-tag">Rules</span>
          <strong>Clear rules make the game easier to enjoy.</strong>
          The rules are not the point of the game, but they matter because they keep the game fair
          without needing an organizer to resolve every edge case live.
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="leg-tag">Game design</span>
          <strong>Constraints create the fun.</strong>
          Banning cars, bikes, ferries, and long-distance running makes the public-transit network
          the actual playing field.
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="leg-tag">Community</span>
          <strong>It is fun because people keep showing up.</strong>
          Teams, registration, supplies, accessibility, timing, and feedback loops are the boring
          parts that make the fun part possible.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2 class="sub">Credit</h2>
      <p>
        The public FAQ credits Jeffrey Wang and me as co-creators of Transit Trek, with Jeffrey as
        primary game author, me as team logistics coordinator, and Michael Xing as game coordinator.
        The public website and its code are not mine.
      </p>

      <div class="endlinks">
        <a class="inline-link" href={transitTrekHref} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Transit Trek site</a>
        <a class="inline-link" href="/projects/">All projects</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
